# Claude Code Insights

270 sessions total · 84 analyzed · 790 messages · 2551h · 8 commits
2026-02-11 to 2026-03-19

## At a Glance

**What's working:** You've developed a strong rhythm of using Claude for iterative bug fixing across complex UI work — modal animations, reactive syncing, time range pickers — and you're good at steering Claude back on track when it goes wrong. Your /simplify habit is genuinely effective, catching real issues like stale ref race conditions and duplicated logic that would otherwise ship. The e2e test reliability work (diagnosing flaky tests, optimizing suite performance) stands out as a particularly high-impact use of Claude. See _Impressive Things You Did_.

**What's hindering you:** On Claude's side, it frequently picks the wrong technical approach first (flexbox instead of grid, wrong dayjs tokens, searching the wrong part of the codebase), which burns iteration cycles on rework. On your side, many of these could be short-circuited by being more specific upfront about constraints and scope — specifying exact files, the approach you want, or known limitations of the libraries involved. See _Where Things Go Wrong_.

**Quick wins to try:** Try setting up a **hook** that automatically runs `tsc --noEmit` after Claude makes edits — this would catch the TypeScript errors and wrong API signatures that kept popping up before you even see the code. You could also create a **custom skill** (e.g., `/review-pr`) that bundles your preferred review + simplify + type-check workflow into a single command, since you already do this sequence manually. See _Features to Try_.

